Class JArray

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.danielhildebrandt.JArray

  • public final class JArray
extends Object
    This class contains various methods with the aim of facilitating similar behavior in arrays as in ArrayList. These utility methods can thought of as an extension of those in Arrays.

      • insert

        public static final <E> void insert(E[] arr,
                                    E emptyElem,
                                    int index,
                                    E newElem)
        Inserts the given element at the provided index, moving subsequent elements out of the way to make room. The "empty element" is the element used in the array to represent an empty spot - this is often simply null, but can also be a pseudo-empty element if null is to be considered a valid element.

        This method will not reallocate the array if it is full; the user must check its capacity prior to calling. If it is full, an ArrayStoreException will be thrown. One will also be thrown if the element to be inserted is equal to the empty element, as this could cause holes in the array.

        This method ensures that the receiving array is complete both before and after its execution. Completeness is defined by the array in question having all instances of the empty element placed only at its trailing end. Refer also to isComplete.

        Parameters:
        arr - the array inserted into; the receiving array
        emptyElem - the element representing "nothing" in the array
        index - the index at which to insert
        newElem - the new element to be inserted
        Throws:
        ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException - if the index is less than zero or is greater than the index of the first empty element in the receiving array
        ArrayStoreException - if the receiving array is already full, or if the element to be inserted is equal to the empty element
        IllegalArgumentException - if the receiving array is empty
        IncompleteArrayException - if the receiving array is not complete
        NullPointerException - if the receiving array is a null reference
        See Also:
        isComplete(Object[], Object)

        Inserts zero or more elements into the array provided, moving subsequent elements out of the way to make room. The index provided signifies the point at which the first element in the varargs-array will be inserted; subsequent elements will be placed in the following spaces. The "empty element" is the element used in the array to represent an empty spot - this is often simply null, but can also be a pseudo-empty element if null is to be considered a valid element. If the array of inserted elements is of zero length, this method will return without modification nor error.

        This method will not reallocate the array if there is insufficient space to store the new elements in it; the user must check its capacity prior to calling. If insufficient space is detected, an ArrayStoreException will be thrown. One will also be thrown if the elements to be inserted include one or more instances of the empty element, as this could create holes in the array.

        This method ensures that the receiving array is complete both before and after its execution. Completeness is defined by the array in question having all instances of the empty element placed only at its trailing end. Refer also to isComplete.

      • removeRange

        public static final <E> E[] removeRange(E[] arr,
                                        E emptyElem,
                                        int fromIndex,
                                        int toIndex)
        Removes all elements from fromIndex, inclusive, to toIndex, exclusive, shifting subsequent elements into the gap. This method then also returns an array containing the removed elements, in the order in which they were previously found in the removal array. The "empty element" is the element used in the array to represent an empty spot - this is often simply null, but can also be a pseudo-empty element if null is to be considered a valid element.

        If fromIndex and toIndex are equal, the single element at this shared index will be removed and returned (in other words, the lower bound's closed-ness will take precedence).

        This method ensures that the array is complete both before and after its execution. Completeness is defined by the array in question having all instances of the empty element placed only at its trailing end. Refer also to isComplete.

        Parameters:
        arr - the array from which to remove one or more elements
        emptyElem - the element representing "nothing" in the array
        fromIndex - the index of the first removed element, inclusive
        toIndex - the index of the last element to remove, exclusive
        Returns:
        an array containing the removed elements
        Throws:
        ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException - if either fromIndex or toIndex is negative; if fromIndex is greater than or equal to the index of the first empty element; or if toIndex is strictly greater than that same empty-index
        IllegalArgumentException - if the array provided is empty, or if fromIndex > toIndex
        IncompleteArrayException - if the array removed from is not complete
        NullPointerException - if the array provided is a null reference

The "empty element" is the element used in the array to represent an empty spot - this is often simply null, but can also be a pseudo-empty element if null is to be considered a valid element.

        This method ensures that the array is complete both before and after its execution. Completeness is defined by the array in question having all instances of the empty element placed only at its trailing end. Refer also to isComplete.

        Parameters:
        arr - arr the array from which to remove zero or more elements
        emptyElem - the element representing "nothing" in the array
        removed - a collection of elements to remove
        Returns:
        a Collection of the elements successfully removed (a subset of removed)
        See Also:
        isComplete(Object[], Object)

      • isComplete

        public static final <E> boolean isComplete(E[] arr,
                                           E emptyElem)
        Returns whether the array provided is "complete," in the sense that the word is also used to describe the array backing a binary heap.

        A complete array is one which has an unbroken sequence of non-empty elements at its beginning, and zero or more empty elements at its end, given a definition of such an "empty element." Often, for example, this would be the value null. This could alternatively be taken as saying that the complete array has no holes in its midst. An empty array is considered as complete.

        Examples of complete arrays:
        ["one", "two", "three", "four", "five"]
        ["one", "two", "three", null, null]
        [null, null, null, null, null]
        [ ]

        Example of incomplete arrays:
        ["one", null, "three", "four", "five"]
        ["one", null, "three", "four", null]
        [null, "two", "three", "four", "five"]

        Parameters:
        arr - the array checked for completeness
        emptyElem - the element representing "nothing" in the array
        Returns:
        true: the array is "complete," having the empty-element occurring only at the trailing end or not at all
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the array provided is a null reference
        See Also:
        IncompleteArrayException

      • isSorted

        public static final <E extends Comparable<? super E>> boolean isSorted(E[] arr)
        Returns whether the given array is sorted, in line with the natural ordering of its elements. This method will ignore any instances of null within the array - as the contract of the Comparable interface specifies that comparison with null should throw an exception - skipping over and straddling any such holes in the array.

        An empty array, or one with but a single element, is considered to be sorted.

        Parameters:
        arr - the array checked for ordering
        Returns:
        true: the array is sorted (in ascending order), according to the natural ordering of its elements
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - is the array provided is a null reference

      • isSorted

        public static final <E> boolean isSorted(E[] arr,
                                         Comparator<? super E> comp)
        Returns whether the given array is sorted, in line with the total ordering of the comparator provided. No special behavior is applied for null elements within the array: if the comparator supplied throws an exception on encountering one, this method will do nothing to stop it.

        An empty array, or one with but a single element, is considered to be sorted.

        Parameters:

        comp - the comparator which specifies the array's imposed ordering
        Returns:
        true: the array is sorted, according to the total ordering imposed by the comparator
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if the array or comparator is a null reference

        public static final int nthIndexOf(byte[] arr,
                                   byte key,
                                   int n)

        Returns the index of the nth value encountered equal to that input, or a negative number if the array contains an insufficient number of equal values. This search is linear.

        If an insufficient number of equivalent values are encountered by the time the entire array has been searched, the number returned is equal to -(reps) - 1, where reps is the number of repetitions of the given value present in the array.

        Parameters:

        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if n if nonpositive
